---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Research">

  <!-- Page header -->
  <div class="mb-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-4">Research</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed">
      My research spans five interconnected areas — mineral spectroscopy, AI-enabled hyperspectral imaging,
      planetary materials science, biosignatures and early life, and Arctic environmental geochemistry — united
      by a common analytical toolkit and a shared commitment to connecting planetary science with urgent Earth
      applications.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Area 1: Mineral Spectroscopy & Remote Sensing -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">
      Mineral Spectroscopy &amp; Remote Sensing
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
      <p>
        I develop and maintain one of the most comprehensive laboratory spectral reference collections in
        geoscience, spanning ultraviolet through thermal infrared wavelengths across oxides, sulphates,
        sulphides, phyllosilicates, carbonates, and evaporites. This foundational work — built to support
        planetary exploration — enables quantitative mineral identification in rocks, soils, drill core,
        and remote sensing products wherever reflectance spectra can be measured.
      </p>
      <p>
        My 2018 Icarus study on the spectral reflectance of magnetite (Izawa et al. 2018, Icarus) directly
        enabled the OSIRIS-REx science team to confirm magnetite on asteroid Bennu and map its spatial
        distribution across the surface. The same magnetite spectral data apply equally to iron ore
        exploration and remote sensing of magnetite-bearing formations on Earth.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-sm p-5">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">Industry Applications</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-[var(--color-text)]">
        <li><strong>Critical mineral exploration</strong> — reflectance spectroscopy for rapid, non-destructive mineral identification in drill core and outcrop</li>
        <li><strong>Iron ore and magnetite deposit remote sensing</strong> — spectral discrimination of magnetite-bearing formations at regional scale</li>
        <li><strong>Mineral identification across UV to thermal IR</strong> — full-wavelength-range identification for geological survey, mine planning, and environmental mapping</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Area 2: AI-Enabled Mineral Intelligence -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">
      AI-Enabled Mineral Intelligence
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
      <p>
        Building on my spectral reference databases, I lead the development of machine-learning workflows
        for automated mineral mapping from hyperspectral imagery. My methods integrate supervised and
        unsupervised classification, spectral unmixing, and deep learning architectures trained on
        laboratory-validated reference datasets — scaling from hand samples and drill core to UAV-mounted
        sensors and satellite imagery.
      </p>
      <p>
        I currently lead the hyperspectral imaging component of a 300-million-yen instrument acquisition
        under the J-PEAKS consortium at Okayama University. This infrastructure directly supports the
        development of AI-enabled mineral intelligence tools that are operational from the benchtop to
        regional survey scale.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-sm p-5">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">Industry Applications</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-[var(--color-text)]">
        <li><strong>Automated drill core mineral mapping</strong> — hyperspectral imaging with AI classification for high-throughput logging of drill core</li>
        <li><strong>Field-portable and UAV-mounted sensor analysis</strong> — rapid outcrop and regional mapping without laboratory turnaround</li>
        <li><strong>Satellite-scale mineral classification</strong> — machine learning applied to next-generation hyperspectral satellite data for exploration programs</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Area 3: Planetary Materials (Meteorites) -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">
      Planetary Materials
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
      <p>
        My laboratory spectroscopy and geochemistry of meteorites, asteroid samples, and Mars analogues
        has generated calibration datasets that directly serve planetary missions. This includes X-ray
        diffraction and infrared spectroscopy of the Tagish Lake carbonaceous chondrite (Izawa et al. 2010,
        Meteoritics &amp; Planetary Science) and, most recently, shock quantification in enstatite
        chondrites (Izawa et al. 2025, Planetary and Space Science) — a first-author contribution
        demonstrating the precision with which laboratory methods can resolve impact histories in
        extraterrestrial materials.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am a science team member on OSIRIS-REx and have contributed to Dawn and Mars Science Laboratory
        science. My credentials include Hayabusa-2 sample handling, extending my work to the most precious
        and analytically demanding planetary materials returned to Earth.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-sm p-5">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">Industry Applications</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-[var(--color-text)]">
        <li><strong>Calibration datasets for asteroid and planetary remote sensing</strong> — laboratory-validated spectral libraries supporting mission instrument calibration</li>
        <li><strong>Carbon and organic material spectral characterization</strong> — subsurface mapping of carbon-bearing geological formations</li>
        <li><strong>Space resource characterization</strong> — sample return mission support and in-situ resource identification for commercial and government programs</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Area 4: Biosignatures & Early Life -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">
      Biosignatures &amp; Early Life
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
      <p>
        I study the detection and preservation of biosignatures in geological materials — a field where the
        same spectroscopic methods used to search for life on Mars have direct application to environmental
        monitoring and altered terrain characterization on Earth. My discovery of titanite mineralization
        within microbial etching textures in Jurassic seafloor basalt (Izawa et al. 2019, Frontiers in
        Microbiology) demonstrated that ancient basaltic sequences can preserve ichnofossil records far older
        than previously recognized. Collaborative work with Applin, Cloutis and colleagues showed that
        oxalate minerals — biologically produced and potentially widespread on Mars — are stable under
        Martian surface conditions, reinterpreting data from Viking, Phoenix, and MSL (Applin, Izawa,
        Cloutis et al. 2015, Earth and Planetary Science Letters).
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-sm p-5">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">Industry Applications</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-[var(--color-text)]">
        <li><strong>Environmental geochemical risk assessment</strong> — secondary mineral characterization in hydrothermally altered and volcanically active terrains</li>
        <li><strong>Altered volcanic system characterization</strong> — spectroscopic mapping of secondary mineral assemblages relevant to geothermal, mining, and environmental contexts</li>
        <li><strong>Permafrost volatile cycling assessment</strong> — geochemical indicators linking biosignature science to Arctic methane and CO₂ flux monitoring</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Area 5: Arctic & Environmental Geochemistry -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">
      Arctic &amp; Environmental Geochemistry
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
      <p>
        Arctic and sub-Arctic environments are undergoing geochemical changes of direct relevance to
        northern communities, resource development, and environmental policy. My fieldwork at the Haughton
        impact structure on Devon Island (Izawa et al. 2011, Astrobiology) and collaborative work on the
        Rio Tinto acid drainage system (Fernandez-Remolar et al. 2018, American Mineralogist) have built
        a comparative framework connecting analogue geochemistry to real-world environmental monitoring.
        Permafrost thaw is exposing sulphide-bearing bedrock to weathering — a process directly analogous
        to acid rock drainage — and I am developing spectroscopic tools to detect and monitor these
        early-stage chemical signatures remotely.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-sm p-5">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-3">Industry Applications</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-[var(--color-text)]">
        <li><strong>Acid rock drainage detection and monitoring</strong> — spectroscopic identification of sulphide oxidation products for environmental risk assessment</li>
        <li><strong>Permafrost thaw geochemical risk assessment</strong> — early-warning monitoring of geochemical change in northern watersheds</li>
        <li><strong>Environmental baseline characterization</strong> — northern resource development support through geochemical mapping and monitoring frameworks</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
